Architecture plan for issues #79-#82

Project shape
- `chen-hatti-f810-personal-site` is a static academic personal website built with Next.js App Router, React, TypeScript, and Tailwind CSS.
- The requested work is presentation/content-asset focused only: no database, auth flow, API route, or runtime object-storage feature is needed.
- Content remains centralized in `data/config.ts` and typed by `data/types.ts`; static assets live in `public/assets`.

Module structure and file organization
- `app/globals.css`
  - Primary target for #79 base typography. Lower the global `body` font size/line-height if the issue should affect all pages consistently.
  - Preserve global focus states, selection styling, and `prefers-reduced-motion` behavior.
- `tailwind.config.ts`
  - Secondary target for #79 if compact typography also benefits from smaller shared spacing tokens (`section`, `card`, etc.). Avoid broad palette changes.
- `components/ui/section-heading.tsx`
  - Adjust section heading size/margins for #79 so all homepage section titles step down consistently.
- `components/sections/hero-section.tsx`
  - Adjust hero name/title/body text sizes for #79.
  - No layout rewrite is required unless the typography reduction exposes spacing issues.
- `components/sections/news-timeline-section.tsx`
  - Main target for #80. Replace the current timeline marker/dot/line layout with a compact single-line row list: date column on the left, title/content on the right, thin dividers between entries.
  - Remove homepage rendering of news descriptions and venues for this simplified treatment unless the issue's wording requires title/content to include a short title only.
- `components/sections/selected-publications-section.tsx`
  - Main target for #81. Replace the outer shared `Card` plus inner `divide-y` container with one `Card` per selected publication and spacing between cards.
  - Keep existing selected-publications filtering and resource link helpers.
- `data/config.ts`
  - Main content pointer update for #82. Change `siteContent.profile.avatar` to `/assets/profile-photo.png`, update alt text to describe the white smiling dog photo, and set dimensions to match the asset.
- `public/assets/profile-photo.png`
  - New repo-bundled image asset for #82. The uploaded/user-provided image should be committed here; do not introduce an upload flow.

Shared types and data
- Existing `ImageAsset` in `data/types.ts` already supports `src`, `alt`, `width`, and `height`; #82 should not require type changes.
- Existing `NewsItem` and `PublicationItem` types are sufficient for #80/#81; these are rendering changes, not data model changes.
- Keep asset references root-relative (`/assets/...`) to continue working with `next/image` and files under `public/`.

Dependencies and sequencing
1. #79 should land first because typography scale affects the visual density of every subsequent section change.
2. #80 can follow #79; it depends only on the current news collection and section component.
3. #81 can be implemented independently of #80 after #79, but should reuse the adjusted compact card/typography scale.
4. #82 is independent of the layout issues, except that final visual review should happen after #79 so the new avatar is checked at the final rendered size.

Key design decisions
- Prefer targeted edits to existing components rather than introducing new layout abstractions for these small UI changes.
- Preserve route structure, static rendering, dark-mode classes, focus states, and responsive behavior.
- Keep `Card`, `SectionHeading`, and content config as the main shared primitives instead of duplicating styling logic.
- Treat the dog avatar as a static, committed asset; do not add S3/object-storage runtime code.
- Maintain accessibility: descriptive image alt text, semantic headings, `time` elements for dates, and readable focus styles.

Verification strategy
- For each issue, run `npm run typecheck`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build`.
- Smoke check `/` after all visual changes.
- For #80 and #81, inspect mobile and desktop widths to ensure rows/cards remain readable and dividers/spacing are correct.
- For #82, confirm `public/assets/profile-photo.png` exists and the rendered avatar uses that file with meaningful alt text.
